    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u help me understand how a force majeure clause works if there is a sudden regional power grid failure? like if the supplier cant deliver because the power went out for everyone in that area, does that count as an unforeseeable event under most standard contracts?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A force majeure clause, also known as a \"force of nature\" clause, is designed to provide relief from contractual obligations when an unforeseen event occurs, such as a natural disaster or a sudden regional power grid failure. In most standard contracts, a force majeure event is typically defined as an event that is beyond the control of either party and that makes it impossible or impracticable to perform the contract. The key is that the event must be unforeseeable at the time the contract was entered into, which is why the power grid failure would likely qualify as a force majeure event under most contracts. However, the supplier would need to demonstrate that they had no control over the power grid failure and that it was not a result of their own negligence or failure to maintain the grid in a safe condition.",
      "source": "target",
